<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="137" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="137">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="137">
Externally, the species is very similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. guizhouense" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="guizhouense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">H. guizhouense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. klapperichi" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="klapperichi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">H. klapperichi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. alexpuchneri" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="alexpuchneri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">H. alexpuchneri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, both in colouration and shape, but it differs mainly, in addition to the aedeagus (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 85–89" captionStartId="F17" captionText="Figures 85 - 89. Hesperosoma miwai 85 - 86 habitus 87 - 89 aedeagus, lateral (87) and ventral (88) views, paramere (89). Scale bars: 2 mm (85 - 86), 0.2 mm (87 - 89)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1075.75799.figures85-89" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/620020" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">87-89</figureCitation>
) and geography, by all tibiae being predominantly black.
</paragraph>
